description: A common, round fruit produced by the tree Malus domestica, cultivated in temperate climates.
Any of various perennial plants of the genus Asparagus having leaflike stems, scalelike leaves, and small flowers.
The large, usually yellowish-green or black, pulpy fruit of the avocado tree.
An elongated curved tropical fruit that grows in bunches and has a creamy flesh and a smooth skin.
An annual Asian plant (Cicer arietinum) in the pea family, widely cultivated for the edible seeds in its short inflated pods.
A long, slender variety of green bean.
The meat from a cow, bull or other bovine.
Capsicum annuum, an edible spicy-sweet fruit, originating in the New World.
A crustacean of the infraorder Brachyura, having five pairs of legs, the foremost of which are in the form of claws, and a carapace.
A plant, Brassica oleracea var. italica, of the cabbage family, Brassicaceae; especially, the tree-shaped flower and stalk that are eaten as a vegetable.
An edible plant (Brassica oleracea var. capitata) having a head of green leaves.
A melon of species Cucumis melo subsp. melo with sweet orange flesh, with numerous cultivars in several cultivar groups.
A vegetable with a nutritious, juicy, sweet root that is often orange in colour, Daucus carota, especially the subspecies sativus in the family Apiaceae.
Any fish of the order Siluriformes, mainly found in fresh water, lacking scales, and having barbels like whiskers around the mouth
Brassica oleracea var. botrytis, an annual variety of cabbage, of which the cluster of young flower stalks and buds is eaten as a vegetable.
A European herb (Apium graveolens) of the carrot family.
A dairy product made from curdled or cultured milk.
A domestic fowl, Gallus gallus, especially when young.

A bivalve mollusk of many kinds, especially those that are edible; for example the soft-shell clam (Mya arenaria), the hard clam (Mercenaria mercenaria), the sea clam or hen clam (Spisula solidissima), and other species.
A sea fish, the Gadus morhua.
Maize, a grain crop of the species Zea mays.
A vine in the gourd family, Cucumis sativus.
An aquatic bird of the family Anatidae, having a flat bill and webbed feet.
A European species of flatfish having dull brown colouring with reddish-brown blotches.
The tree of the species Citrus paradisi, a hybrid of pomelo (Citrus maxima) and sweet orange.
A small, round, smooth-skinned edible fruit, usually purple, red, or green, that grows in bunches on vines of genus Vitis.
A large flatfish of the genus Hippoglossus, which sometimes leaves the ocean floor and swims vertically.
A marine fish, Melanogrammus aeglefinus, of the North Atlantic, important as a food fish.
A Chinese gooseberry vine fruit, having a hairy brown skin and dark green (or in the case of the kiwi fruit gold, yellow) flesh with fine black seeds, almost always varieties of Actinidia deliciosa.
A young sheep.
A yellowish citrus fruit.
An edible plant, Lactuca sativa and its close relatives, having a head of green and/or purple leaves.
Any of several green citrus fruit, somewhat smaller and sharper-tasting than a lemon.
A crustacean of the Nephropidae family, dark green or blue-black in colour turning bright red when cooked, with a hard shell and claws, which is used as a seafood.
A white liquid produced by the mammary glands of female mammals to nourish their young.
Any of the fleshy fruiting bodies of fungi typically produced above ground on soil or on their food sources (such as decaying wood).
Widely cultivated cereal grass, typically Avena sativa.
A monocotyledonous plant (Allium cepa), allied to garlic, used as vegetable and spice.
The fruit of an orange tree; a citrus fruit with a slightly sour flavour.

Any of certain marine bivalve mollusks, especially those of the family Ostreidae (the true oysters), usually found adhering to rocks or other fixed objects in shallow water along the seacoasts, or in brackish water in the mouth of rivers.
The soft juicy stone fruit of the peach tree, having yellow flesh, downy, red-tinted yellow skin, and a deeply sculptured pit or stone containing a single seed.
An edible fruit produced by the pear tree, similar to an apple but elongated towards the stem.
A type of short, diagonally cut pasta.
A tropical plant, Ananas comosus, native to South America, having thirty or more long, spined and pointed leaves surrounding a thick stem.
The edible, fleshy stone fruit of Prunus domestica, often of a dark red or purple colour.
The meat of a pig; swineflesh.
A goosefoot (Chenopodium quinoa) native to the Andes and cultivated for its edible seeds.
Rice with the brownish hull not polished off as in white rice.
One of several species of fish, typically of the Salmoninae subfamily, brownish above with silvery sides and delicate pinkish-orange flesh; they ascend rivers to spawn.
Any of various marine bivalve molluscs of the family Pectinidae which are free-swimming.
Any of many swimming, often edible crustaceans, chiefly of the infraorder Caridea or the suborder Dendrobranchiata, with slender legs, long whiskers and a long abdomen.
Cream which has been treated with a benign bacterium to turn it slightly sour, often used as a condiment, or a topping for baked potatoes.
The sweet, usually red, edible fruit of certain plants of the genus Fragaria.
A tropical perennial American vine, Ipomoea batatas, having a fleshy tuber.
A large marine fish with a long, pointed bill, Xiphias gladius.
Any of several varieties of mandarin oranges.
A widely cultivated plant, Solanum lycopersicum, having edible fruit.
Any of several species of fish of the genus Thunnus in the family Scombridae.
Either of two species of bird in the genus Meleagris with fan-shaped tails and wattled necks.
A plant tuber, Solanum tuberosum, eaten as a starchy vegetable, particularly in the Americas and Europe.
A milk-based product stiffened by a bacterium-aided curdling process, and sometimes mixed with fruit or other flavoring.
